==Reception== [[Thomas Pogge]]<ref>{{cite book |last1=Pogge |first1=Thomas |title=Shue on Rights and Duties |date=2011 |url=http://www.oxfordscholarship.com/view/10.1093/acprof:osobl/9780199604388.001.0001/acprof-9780199604388-chapter-6 |accessdate=21 August 2018}}</ref>, [[Michael Payne (philosopher)|Michael Payne]]<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Payne |first1=Michael |title=Henry Shue on Basic Rights |journal=[[Essays in Philosophy]] |date=June 2008 |volume=9 |issue=2 |url=https://commons.pacificu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?referer=&httpsredir=1&article=1317&context=eip |accessdate=21 August 2018}}</ref>, and [[Andrew Cohen (philosopher)|Andrew Cohen]]<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Cohen |first1=Andrew I. |title=Must Rights Impose Enforceable Positive Duties? |journal=[[Journal of Social Philosophy]] |date=June 2004 |volume=35 |issue=2 |pages=264–276 |doi=10.1111/j.1467-9833.2004.00231.x |url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/pdf/10.1111/j.1467-9833.2004.00231.x |accessdate=21 August 2018 |language=en |issn=0047-2786}}</ref> criticized Shue's ideas on [[basic rights]]. [[Jordan Kiper]] provided a defense of Shue's arguments for basic rights.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kiper |first1=Jordan |title=Henry Shue on Basic Rights: A Defense |journal=[[Human Rights Review]] |date=2 April 2011 |volume=12 |issue=4 |pages=505–514 |doi=10.1007/s12142-011-0197-8 |url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s12142-011-0197-8 |accessdate=21 August 2018 |language=en |issn=1524-8879}}</ref>
