In [[English law|English legal]] proceedings, a '''confidentiality club''' (also known as '''confidentiality ring''')<ref>{{cite book|last1=Sime|first1=Stuart|last2=French|first2=Derek|title=Blackstone's Civil Practice 2013: The Commentary|year=2012|publisher=Oxford University Press|at=48.35|isbn=9780191645495}}</ref> is an agreement occasionally reached by parties to a [[litigation]] to reduce the risk of [[confidential]] documents being used outside the litigation. The agreement typically provides that only specified persons can access some documents. Setting up a confidentiality club "requires some degree of cooperation between the parties".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Cook|first1=Trevor|last2=Garcia|first2=Alejandro I.|title=International Intellectual Property Arbitration - Volume 2 of Arbitration in context series|year=2010|publisher=Kluwer Law International BV|isbn=9789041127259|page=265}}</ref> Confidentiality clubs were described in 2012 as being increasingly common.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Matthews|first1=Paul|last2=Malek|first2=Hodge M.|title=Disclosure|year=2012|publisher=Sweet & Maxwell|isbn=9780414047792|page=441}}</ref>

